 1394","abt 1377":"about 1377","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","of Toomer, Som, Eng.":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Toomer, Henstridge, Somerset, England":"Henstridge, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Toomer, Somerset, England":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Moyne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  Norman, English: nickname from Old French  <i>moine</i>, Anglo-Norman French  <i>muine</i>,  <i>moingne</i> ‘monk’. Some of the following early bearers without the definite article could alternatively belong with (2).","2  English:  see  Moon   (1)."],"variants":[{"name":"Moin","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Moyne</b>, a nickname from Old French <i>moine</i>, Anglo-Norman French <i>muine</i>, <i>moingne</i> ‘monk’.","Muslim (mainly the Indian subcontinent): unexplained."]},{"name":"Moon","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Mohan  .","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Moyon in La Manche. Compare   Mounce  .","Americanized form of German   Mohn   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Moynan","meanings":["Irish: perhaps a diminutive of   Moyne   or a reduced form of   Moynihan  ."]},{"name":"Moine","meanings":["French: from <i>moine</i> ‘monk’, probably applied as an occupational name for a servant at a monastery or an ironic nickname for someone of monkish behavior or appearance. Compare   Lemoine  ."]},{"name":"Moynes","meanings":["English: variant of   Moyne   with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Elizabeth Moyne was born in 1336, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom, her father, John Moyne, was 22 and her mother, Joan Belvale, was -15. She married John De Toomer. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1404, at the age of 68."},"et":{"1336–1404":"1336–1404","1332–1394":"1332–1394","1349–1414":"1349–1414","1377–1409":"1377–1409","1314–Male":"1314–Surnud","1351–Female":"1351–Surnud","1349":"1349","1404":"1404","1414":"1414","1336":"1336","1314":"1314","1377":"1377","1332":"1332","1351":"1351","1394":"1394","1409":"1409","about 1394":"umbes 1394","abt 1377":"umbes 1377","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of Toomer, Som, Eng.":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Toomer, Henstridge, Somerset, England":"Henstridge, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Toomer, Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1336–1404":"1336–1404","1332–1394":"1332–1394","1349–1414":"1349–1414","1377–1409":"1377–1409","1314–Male":"1314–Kuollut","1351–Female":"1351–Kuollut","1349":"1349","1404":"1404","1414":"1414","1336":"1336","1314"